
[1]sociable

   SO'CIABLE, a. [L. sociabilis, from socius, a companion, probably from
   sequor, to follow. See Seek.]

   1. That may be conjoined; fit to be united in one body or company; as
   sociable parts united in one body.

   2. Ready or disposed to unite in a general interest. To make man mild,
   and sociable to man.

   3. Ready and inclined to join in company or society; or frequently
   meeting for conversation; as sociable neighbors.

   4. Inclined to converse when in company; disposed to freedom in
   conversation; opposed to reserved and taciturn.

   5. Free in conversation; conversing much or familiarly. The guests were
   very sociable.
